Here's an example of how to generate a table of contents (TOC) automatically in a LaTeX document using the `tableofcontents` and `\section`, `\subsection`, `\subsubsection` commands:

**example.tex**
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\begin{document}

\tableofcontents

\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}

Some text in the introduction.

\subsection{Background}
\label{sec:intro:bg}

More text in the background section.

\subsubsection{Related Work}
\label{sec:intro:bg:rw}

Citations and references to related work.

\section{Methodology}
\label{sec:method}

This is the methodology section.

\subsection{Data Collection}
\label{sec:method:dc}

How we collected the data.

\subsubsection{Data Analysis}
\label{sec:method:da}

How we analyzed the data.

\end{document}
```
**Compiling the document:**

Run `pdflatex example.tex` (or `latex` followed by `bibtex` and another `pdflatex` if you have bibliography) to compile the document.

**Output:**

The resulting PDF file will have a automatically generated table of contents at the beginning, like this:

**Table of Contents**

1. Introduction ....................................................... 1
    1.1 Background ................................................... 1
        1.1.1 Related Work ........................................ 1
2. Methodology ....................................................... 2
    2.1 Data Collection ........................................... 2
        2.1.1 Data Analysis ...................................... 2

Note that the TOC will automatically update whenever you modify the sectioning commands in your document.

The `\tableofcontents` command is part of the LaTeX kernel, so you don't need to load any additional packages to use it. Just be sure to include it before the first sectioning command in your document.

